<br>
I also agree that the Dems do not have a chance this year.  I'm pleased to see that they seem to be backing away from wild man Dean.  I would prefer that Bush's Democratic opponent not be an extremist, for two reasons:<br>
<br>
1.  Even though an extremist would be easier to beat, having a more centrist opponent would force Bush to shore up his Conservative base.  Tax cuts are great, but Bush has shown no spending restraint.  And GOP spending cannot be justified by the war, because non-defense discretionary spending has gone wild, too.<br>
2.  The Dem might win.  Better to have a reasonable Dem than a wild man.<br>
<br>
That said, I don't think the Dems have a chance in heck.  Look, every one of them is on record that they will repeal the Bush tax cuts.  That's a guaranteed losing position.  They will never convince people in a recession that they need to surrender even more of their money, nor convince them that taking money from businesses is going to encourage the businesses to start hiring the unemployed.<br>
<br>
It's really just a question of whether the landslide will take in all 50 states.<br>
<br>
50 states/ 535 electoral votes!<br>
